{"id":"2205.11313","submitter":"Chenyang Xu","authors":"Chenyang Xu and Pinyan Lu","title":"Mechanism Design with Predictions","comments":"To appear in IJCAI 2022","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.GT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Improving algorithms via predictions is a very active research topic in\nrecent years. This paper initiates the systematic study of mechanism design in\nthis model. In a number of well-studied mechanism design settings, we make use\nof imperfect predictions to design mechanisms that perform much better than\ntraditional mechanisms if the predictions are accurate (consistency), while\nalways retaining worst-case guarantees even with very imprecise predictions\n(robustness). Furthermore, we refer to the largest prediction error sufficient\nto give a good performance as the error tolerance of a mechanism, and observe\nthat an intrinsic tradeoff among consistency, robustness and error tolerance is\ncommon for mechanism design with predictions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 23 May 2022 13:56:41 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 12 Jan 2023 16:11:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-13"}
